issue.title: macos: shutdown on first run due to -psn_ parameter
issue.body:
When downloading and running Bitcoin core for the first time, after clicking through the "Are you sure you want to open. it?" screen, there's a possibility that macOS will pass an argument like `-psn_0_SOME_ID` to the application, which results in a shutdown as it's an invalid argument:

![v0 19 0rc1 args shutdown](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/863730/67034964-b026fc00-f0e6-11e9-8462-70d0fcf613e6.png)

This only happens on the first run, subsequent opens will work fine, but we should filter these out, otherwise it's a poor and confusing first experience.

events.body:
ACK b5f0be38790ecc87a1e537edeca5923f608bc68c

I agree it's a hack, but it's also harmless, and apparently the same Qt used to do, when we still passed the command line arguments to it.

issue.title: Replace #16578 with a more specific solution
issue.body:
The change in #16578, although necessary, was over-sweeping.

I was initially in favor of it, but never expected this. It is turning into a boondoggle, with repercussions from our testing process (#17013) to MacOS user experience (#17025, #17179). Even changes outside the GUI code itself (#17184). I feel this is getting out of hand. It creates a lot of work and we'll end up reverting all of this eventually.

events.body: ACK b5f0be38790ecc87a1e537edeca5923f608bc68c - Tested that this fixes #17179.
